#X text 31 435 Noise sources are also suitable for filtering in subtractive synthesis. Here's [noise~] going through [bandpass~] \, a filter that only passes a band/range of frequency and whose resonance controls the width of this frequency band. For a vey high Q/Resonance \, note how we can perceive a clear pitch., f 63;
#X obj 90 274 bl.saw~ 50;
#X obj 131 329 lowpass~ 500 10;
#X text 39 126 We've seen basic filters in the previous part. In short \, to filter a sound is to either attenuate or boost some of its frequency content. Most commonly \, subtractive synthesis uses Lowpass Resonant filters \, such as [lowpass~] from ELSE \, which "passes" frequencies below the resonant frequency and a resonance parameter boosts the resonant frequency., f 62;
#X text 506 57 Even though we usually need some sort of filter modulation \, many syntyhesizers that are consider "subtractive" might simply have a non modulated filter in the process chain., f 44;
