#X text 554 583 The same patch with MERDA modules., f 19;
#X text 550 637 Next examples will include proper modulations., f 26;
#X text 506 130 Actually \, many subtractive synths will actually have more than one oscillator and adding them (aka wave stacking) is even more important in the sound design process. So don't let commonly applied terminology deceive you., f 44;
#X text 506 224 Hence \, subtractive synths are better described as modular systems where you can combine oscillators \, filters and modulate them with LFOs \, envelopes and such \, because \, yes \, filter modulation is not the only modulating possibility usually. Hence \, arguably \, subtractive synthesis could be treated under the 'Modulation.Synthesis' part that comes next in this tutorial. And also \, the techniques we'll see later in that section can also include modulation of filter that we know as "subtractive synthesis"., f 44;
#X text 39 20 Subtractive Synthesis is a technique that can be generalized as simply applying filtering to a sound source. It needs to be a rich and complex sound source like a sawtooth oscillator. Particularly \, the filter must be slowly modulated somehow \, such as via Low Frequency Oscillarors/Noise and envelope as we'll see. Otherwise \, it's simply applying another FX and there's nothing special to it., f 62;
#X text 506 424 For now we'll expand on an earlier example we've seen in the sequencing section and increment on the sound design principles. Instead of a single oscillator going through an envelope generator \, we combine two detuned oscillators and filter them., f 44;
